14 recognized reference; and that there are at least two therapeutically equivalent, multiple source
15 drugs, or at least one generic drug available from one manufacturer, available for purchase by
16 network pharmacies from national or regional wholesalers.
17 (c) If a drug that has been placed on a maximum allowable cost list no longer meets the
18 requirements of subsection (a), the drug shall be removed from the maximum allowable cost list
19 by the pharmacy benefits manager or covered entity within 3 business days after the drug no
20 longer meets the requirements of subsection (a).
21 (d) A pharmacy benefits manager or covered entity shall make available to each
22 pharmacy with which the pharmacy benefits manager or covered entity has a contract and to
23 each pharmacy included in a network of pharmacies served by a pharmacy services
24 administrative organization
25 with which the pharmacy benefits manager or covered entity has a contract, at the
26 beginning of the term of a contract upon renewal of a contract, or upon request:
27 (1) The sources used to determine the maximum allowable costs for the drugs and
28 medical products and devices on each maximum allowable cost list;
29 (2) Every maximum allowable cost for individual drugs used by that pharmacy benefits
30 manager or covered entity for patients served by that contracted pharmacy; and
31 (3) Upon request, every maximum allowable cost list used by that pharmacy benefits
32 manager or covered entity for patients served by that contracted pharmacy.
33 (e) A pharmacy benefits manager or covered entity shall:
